An analysis of waiting time for different SNR values averaged across all trial types (correct and incorrect) revealed a significant drug √ó SNR √ó brain region interaction (GLM; Ì†µÌ∞π(7,1750) = 282, Ì†µÌ±ù = 7.07 √ó 10=EVE, adjusted Ì†µÌ±ÖE = 0.529; three-way interaction: Ì†µÌªΩ = 1.66, Ì†µÌ±ù = 1.94 √ó 10=>). When the trial type (correct vs incorrect) was included as a withinsubject factor, there was similarly a significant trial type √ó drug √ó brain region interaction (GLM; Ì†µÌ∞π(15,1742) = 327, Ì†µÌ±ù = 10=M?, adjusted Ì†µÌ±ÖE = 0.735, three-way interaction: Ì†µÌªΩ = 1.84, Ì†µÌ±ù = 7.40 √ó 10=T). These results show that inhibition of ACC or BLA affect rats‚Äô willingness to wait depending on SNR (perceptual uncertainty) as well as based on whether their response was correct or incorrect.
Given these interaction effects, we then measured the influence of inhibition of ACC and BLA on waiting time separately for each value of SNR. We found that overall, inhibition of ACC significantly increased waiting time compared to vehicle (diff(mean)=3.45 sec; GLM; Ì†µÌ∞π(1,1288) = 204, Ì†µÌ±ù = 4.98 √ó 10=\O, adjusted Ì†µÌ±ÖE = 0.136; drug: Ì†µÌªΩ = 3.45, Ì†µÌ±ù = 4.98 √ó 10=\O; Figure 3A,C). In contrast, inhibition of BLA significantly reduced rats‚Äô overall willingness to wait before re-initiation of a new trial (diff(mean)=-4.59sec; GLM; Ì†µÌ∞π(1,1348) = 388, Ì†µÌ±ù = 4.87 √ó 10=?T, adjusted Ì†µÌ±ÖE = 0.223; drug: Ì†µÌªΩ = ‚àí4.58, Ì†µÌ±ù = 4.86 √ó 10=?T; Figure 3B,C). Importantly, we found a significant interaction of SNR by drug condition (CNO vs. vehicle administration) for ACC (GLM; SNR √ó drug: Ì†µÌªΩ = ‚àí2.19, Ì†µÌ±ù = 1.78 √ó 10=MN), indicating that the observed increase in waiting time due to ACC inhibition depended on SNR. In contrast, the decrease in waiting time due to BLA inhibition was not SNR-specific (GLM; SNR √ó drug: Ì†µÌªΩ = ‚àí0.3434, Ì†µÌ±ù = 0.16), indicating that BLA inhibition increased sensitivity to delays (or equivalently increased impulsivity), as has been reported before (Winstanley, Theobald, Cardinal, & Robbins, 2004). Finally, we found similar results when we performed our analyses for each value of contrast separately (Supplementary Figure 3A-C).
Despite strong, dissociable effects on waiting time, inhibition of ACC and BLA did not change the overall task performance, discrimination accuracy, response bias, or reaction time. First, probability of correct response was not significantly different between vehicle and CNO
